From the manufacturer

ScreenBar is a revolutionary lighting system. Simply hang it on your monitor to light up your desk without taking up any valuable space. With automatic dimmer and asymmetric optical design, ScreenBar illuminates the working space with just USB power, avoiding reflectively glare off your computer screen.

Description

BenQ screen bar e-reading LED monitor lamp with auto-dimming and hue adjustment features matte Black USB powered office lamp (ScreenBar_Black)

Features & details

Features

  • Comply with standard light level comply with American National Standard practice for office lighting 500 lux recommendation (1000 lux in the center)
  • Auto-dimming using a built-in ambient light sensor screen Bar adjusts the brightness level throughout the day for a eye-healthy workspace It can also be manually dimmed with the touch control
  • Hue adjustment Adjustable color temperature to provide focus and comfort Warm light for relaxing cool light for work efficiency
  • No screen glare Its asymmetrical Optical design only illuminates the desk and eliminates reflective glare off the screen found on most regular desk lamps
  • Space saving breakthrough design mounts on top of the monitor saving valuable space on your desk
  • Fits nearly any monitor the weighted clip gently rests on nearly any monitor with thickness from 0 4" To 1 2" (1 to 3 cm)

BENQ, Thank you!!!

getsomesleep
5.0 out of 5 starsVerified Purchase
Reviewed in the United States on October 22, 2018
Style: ScreenBar w/ Dial
Premium! Buy it once, for life.
For the past few years, I've wondered how I could evenly distribute light across my small work space without adding a light fixture directly on my wall. Corner lights are not sufficient and brighten the whole room leaving my work space unfocused. Then I found BenQ... See more
For the past few years, I've wondered how I could evenly distribute light across my small work space without adding a light fixture directly on my wall. Corner lights are not sufficient and brighten the whole room leaving my work space unfocused. Then I found BenQ screenlight after seeing a review for their eReader light which I might also purchase in the near future. After seeing all the positive reviews on youtube I went ahead and made the splurge.

I went for the BenQ with Dial version, set it up less than a minute, and it's absolutely perfect. Not only does it feel premium, the functionality is also premium -- the ambient light sensor is giving me a bright white light which resonates off my white desk without any glare. The Dial that comes with the "plus" version feels solid. There are 2 buttons on it, one for ambient light sensor, and another button to toggle between a) light brightness, b) light color, which both work with the knob for adjustments. Pressing down on the knob will turn the light on/off. I would imagine adjusting the light without the Dial as tedious, so I recommend spending the extra $30 for it. I didn't know the "plus" version does not have buttons on the top, its all from the dial.

Do I think it is expensive? Yes, and even now I feel a bit guilty. However, I can find the value in its premium build and functionality, and I know this is a purchase that will last a long, long time. There is absolutely nothing I can think of that this light can do better assuming you have the "Plus" version that comes with the light dial, which allows me to make fast adjustments without clicking the light itself (which some reviewers complained about). The BenQ Screenlight with Dial is one of those "buy for life" purchases, and knowing that LED bulbs last a long time these days, I can have peace of mind.

Highly recommended.

By the way, my workspace is a small IKEA micke desk, only 29 inches wide, with a 30" monitor and a 24" monitor on a monitor arm, on the side. With such a small space the light was a perfect solution. Please see photo.

Simple
5.0 out of 5 starsVerified Purchase
Reviewed in the United States on October 24, 2018
Style: ScreenBar w/ Dial
Sits nicely on the LG 27MD5KB-B connected to my MacBook Pro. Light works flawlessly!
My office has blackout blinds and I have very dim blue lighting in the room to keep the mood cool. I ran into two challenges which led me to purchasing this light over anything else. My company is now using Zoom for conferencing and encourages everyone to join on video.... See more
My office has blackout blinds and I have very dim blue lighting in the room to keep the mood cool. I ran into two challenges which led me to purchasing this light over anything else. My company is now using Zoom for conferencing and encourages everyone to join on video. With my room being dark and the ceiling light having a dim blue bulb, no one could see me. The other challenge is I started watching training videos and want to take hand written notes in a notebook. It's not enjoyable doing this in the dark and it's impossible to read my notes or even read a book. I needed something..

I first saw a review for the BenQ desk lamp which people praised but I did not want a lamp taking up desk space. Then I saw the link for this one, the BenQ e-Reading that sits on your monitor, and decided to order it. I have no regrets. It's well worth the price. I purchased the version with the dial which allows you to turn the light on and off, adjust brightness, adjust temperature, and toggle auto-adjust on/off where the light sets the temperature automatically based on the room. The censor for this is on the dial.

The light itself does everything I want. It provides plenty of light for video calls on my Mac or when reading books or taking notes. It can be rotated to make sure the light is not shining or reflecting off the monitor screen, only emitting away from the monitor. The counterweight the light bar snaps into lets you adjust the exact position of it sits on the top of the monitor. By default when you set it on top of the LG monitor it looks like it's barely covering the LG's camera, but I was able to make the adjustment so it now sits above the camera and does not get in the way. I have a small non-powered Belkin USB-C hub connected to one of the USB-C ports on the back of the LG. The Blekin has two USB-C and two regular USB ports. The BenQ connect to the Belkin which provides power.

The whole package, dial included, looks elegant and feels sturdy. This was the magic bullet that solved my problem and I'm very happy with it. I would recommend it over a desk lamp. You get all the light you need without it reflecting off the monitor screen and you're not taking up precious desk space.

The BenQ product * Is a 45cm wide somewhat-truncated tube, USB powered, that sits on top of a display * a bar of LEDs is mounted in the tube * there are 2 small flat areas on the top either side of centre which allow adjustment of colour & brightness * the result is an illuminated area, perhaps 100cm wide x 40cm deep * the device requires no fixture to the display as it balances with a rear counterweight in the middle * so the first adjustment is to position the device so the LEDs point down parallel to the display * the second adjustment is to rotate the tube so the LEDs are shielded from direct eyesight by the tube's surface Some comments: * dust on the screen is highlighted when the display is off; if nothing encourages wiping clean with a suitable cloth * I'm currently not running macOS Catalina, but BBEdit and VSCode already default to a dark mode and the dust is not apparent * any keyboard backlighting will probably be washed-out I used to use a small USB-powered LED strip to illuminate my keyboard and desk area, but the BenQ product is much better. I'm giving only 4 stars for now, until I can see it with dark-mode. I don't expect any issues though. NB this is on an iMac with a glossy screen surface.
